{"CLs":[{"__type":"ST","Ix":1,"Var":"Info_Retain"},{"__type":"ST","Var":"Info_General","X":1}],"CMT":"Graphics on the HMI are relatively limited:\u000a- No offset possible between traces\u000a- Only two scales available (left and right)\u000a- Graphs cannot be dynamically displayed or hidden\u000d\u000a- You can't dynamically change min and max scales.\u000a- Having all graphics on the same scale makes the page completely unreadable.\u000d\u000a\u000d\u000aTo get around these problems, I created the following system.\u000a\u000aFirst, the graph will be relative. The values displayed and the viewing area on the HMI will be from 0 to 100, and I'll adapt my values to this\u000d\u000a0..100. This choice also allows me to let the user choose a min and max value, which will be scaled to a 0..100.\u000a\u000aI can also have an option to hide the graph, by forcing my displayed value to -1.\u000a\u000aAnd last but not least, to improve visibility, I've defined 5 display zones, selectable in the structure. \u000d\u000aThese zones are also separated on the HMI by the number of separations on the Y axis. And setting the display to one of these zones will \u000d\u000amodify the output scaling between 100 and 80 for zone 1, 80 and 60 for zone 2, etc...\u000d\u000a\u000d\u000aYou need Retain if you want do remember, position and user limits","LRI":2,"RRI":3,"VLs":[]}
